class.haxe_doc: * MPEG Version * * sored on 2 bits in the file, * values represent bit values
* Layer * * stored on 2 bits in the file, * values represent bit values
* Sound channel mode * * stored on 2 bits in the file, * values represent bit values
* Emphasis * * 2 bits

enum.haxe_doc: * Used by seekFrame to retrun the type * of frame (possibly) found.

skipID3v2.haxe_doc: * Called after found 'ID3' signature * at the beginning of the file. * * Records the raw tag data.

seekFrame.haxe_doc: * Winds the input stream until the 11-bit * syncword is found. * * @returns Bool false if not found (this should happen at eof).

readFrames.haxe_doc: * Returns all valid frames. Invalid frames * are discarded.

readFrameHeader.haxe_doc: * Returns null if header proves to be invalid.

readFrame.haxe_doc: * Reads a frame from the input. * * The input position should already be just past the * 11 bit syncword. * * Returns null if the header is invalid or the frame was incomplete.

read.haxe_doc: * Reads the MP3 data. * * Currently returns all valid frames.

isInvalidFrameHeader.haxe_doc: * Tells whether the header is invalid.

getSampleDataSize.haxe_doc: * Return sample data size. Note that * the 4 bytes subtracted is the size of the header, * so this 4 bytes less the frame size. * * Also, 2 bytes are subtracted for CRC too, if present

getSampleCount.haxe_doc: * Returns the number of samples in the frame.

getFrameInfo.haxe_doc: * Displays frame info in human-readable format. * Subject to change, do not use for programmatical parsing!

getHeader.haxe_doc: Returns the PNG header informations. Throws an exception if no header found.

getPalette.haxe_doc: Return the PNG palette colors, or null if no palette chunk was found

reverseBytes.haxe_doc: Converts from BGRA to ARGB and the other way by reversing bytes.

extractGrey.haxe_doc: Decode the greyscale PNG data and apply filters, extracting only the grey channel if alpha is present.

extract32.haxe_doc: Decode the PNG data and apply filters. By default this will output BGRA low-endian format. You can use the [reverseBytes] function to inverse the bytes to ARGB big-endian format.

buildGrey.haxe_doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains one bytes (grey values) for each pixel.

buildIndexed.haxe_doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains a one byte palette index for each pixel and a separate palette with 3 RGB bytes per color.

buildRGB.haxe_doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains three bytes (R,G and B values) for each pixel.

build32ARGB.haxe_doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains four bytes in ARGB format for each pixel.

build32BGRA.haxe_doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains four bytes in BGRA format for each pixel.

yOrigin.haxe_doc: * These bytes specify the absolute vertical coordinate for the lower left * corner of the image as it is positioned on a display device having an * origin at the lower left of the screen (e.g., the TARGA series).

xOrigin.haxe_doc: * These bytes specify the absolute horizontal coordinate for the lower left * corner of the image as it is positioned on a display device having an * origin at the lower left of the screen (e.g., the TARGA series).

width.haxe_doc: This field specifies the width of the image in pixels.

height.haxe_doc: This field specifies the height of the image in pixels.

colorMapType.haxe_doc: * Indicated type of color map. * 0 = no color map present. * 1 = color map included. * 2-127 is reserved by Truevision * 128-255 may be used by app developers.

colorMapLength.haxe_doc: Total number of color map entries included.

colorMapFirstIndex.haxe_doc: * Index of the first color map entry. Index refers to the starting entry in * loading the color map.

colorMapEntrySize.haxe_doc: * Establishes the number of bits per entry. Typically 15, 16, 24 or 32-bit * values are used.

bitsPerPixel.haxe_doc: * This field indicates the number of bits per pixel. This number includes * the Attribute or Alpha channel bits. Common values are 8, 16, 24 and * 32 but other pixel depths could be used.

alphaChannelBits.haxe_doc: * the number of attribute bits per * pixel. In the case of the TrueVista, these bits * indicate the number of bits per pixel which are * designated as Alpha Channel bits. For the ICB * and TARGA products, these bits indicate the * number of overlay bits available per pixel.

NoImage.haxe_doc: There is no image data present

RunLengthColorMapped.haxe_doc: Run-length encoded image with color-map usage

class.haxe_doc: * ... * @author Yanrishatum

parentContainer.haxe_doc: The parent container of this object. See `Object.contentChanged` for more details.

parent.haxe_doc: The parent object in the scene tree.

numChildren.haxe_doc: How many immediate children this object has.

name.haxe_doc: The name of the object. Can be used to retrieve an object within a tree by using `Object.getObjectByName`.

x.haxe_doc: The x position (in pixels) of the object relative to its parent.

y.haxe_doc: The y position (in pixels) of the object relative to its parent.

scaleX.haxe_doc: The amount of horizontal scaling of this object.

scaleY.haxe_doc: The amount of vertical scaling of this object.

rotation.haxe_doc: The rotation angle of this object, in radians.

visible.haxe_doc: Is the object and its children are displayed on screen.

alpha.haxe_doc: The amount of transparency of the Object.

filter.haxe_doc:
The post process filter for this object.
When set, `Object.alpha` value affects both filter and object transparency (use `Drawable.color.a` to set transparency only for the object).

blendMode.haxe_doc:
The blending mode of the object.
If there is no `Object.filter` active, only applies to the current object (not inherited by children). Otherwise tells how the filter is blended with background.

posChanged.haxe_doc:
A flag that indicates that the object transform was modified and absolute position recalculation is required.
Automatically cleared on `Object.sync` and can be manually synced with the `Object.syncPos`.

allocated.haxe_doc:
A flag that indicates whether the object was allocated or not.
When adding children to allocated objects, `onAdd` is being called immediately, otherwise it's delayed until the whole tree is added to a currently active `Scene`.

getSize.haxe_doc: Similar to `getBounds(parent)`, but instead of the full content, it will return the size based on the alignment of the object. For instance for a text, `Object.getBounds` will return the full glyphs size whereas `getSize` will ignore the pixels under the baseline. @param out An optional bounds instance to fill. Allocates new Bounds instance and returns it if not set.

getAbsPos.haxe_doc: Returns the updated absolute position matrix. See `Object.getMatrix` for current matrix values.

contains.haxe_doc: Tells if the object is contained into this object children, recursively.

find.haxe_doc: Find a single object in the tree by calling `f` on each and returning the first not-null value returned, or null if not found.

findAll.haxe_doc: Find several objects in the tree by calling `f` on each and returning all the not-null values returned. @param arr An optional array instance to fill results with. Allocates a new array if not set.

getObjectsCount.haxe_doc: Return the total number of children in the whole tree, recursively.

localToGlobal.haxe_doc: Convert a local position (or `[0,0]` if `pt` is null) relative to the object origin into an absolute screen position, applying all the inherited transforms. @param pt An optional position to convert and return. Allocates new Point at 0,0 position if not set. Modifies the Point instance as is.

globalToLocal.haxe_doc: Convert an absolute screen position into a local position relative to the object origin, applying all the inherited transforms. @param pt A position to convert and return. Modifies the Point instance as is.

getScene.haxe_doc: Returns an `h2d.Scene` down the hierarchy tree or `null` if object is not added to Scene.

addChild.haxe_doc: Add a child object at the end of the children list.

addChildAt.haxe_doc: Insert a child object at the specified position of the children list.

onContentChanged.haxe_doc: Should be called when Object content was changed in order to notify parent container. See `Object.contentChanged`.

onAdd.haxe_doc:
Sent when object is being added to an allocated scene.
Do not remove the super call when overriding.

onRemove.haxe_doc:
Sent when object is removed from the allocated scene.
Do not remove the super call when overriding.

getMatrix.haxe_doc: Populates Matrix with current absolute object transform values. See `Object.getAbsPos` for up-to-date values.

removeChild.haxe_doc: Remove the given object from the immediate children list of the object if it's part of it.

setParentContainer.haxe_doc: Sets the parent container for this Object and it's children. See `Object.contentChanged` for more details.

removeChildren.haxe_doc: Remove all children from the immediate children list.

remove.haxe_doc: Same as `parent.removeChild(this)`, but does nothing if parent is null.

drawTo.haxe_doc: Draw the object and all its children into the given Texture.

drawToTextures.haxe_doc: Draw the object and all its children into the given Textures.

draw.haxe_doc: Override this method in order to add custom graphics rendering to your Object. `draw` is invoked before rendering of the object children.

sync.haxe_doc:
Performs a sync of data for rendering (such as absolute position recalculation). While this method can be used as a substitute to an update loop, it's primary purpose it to prepare the Object to be rendered.
Do not remove the super call when overriding.

syncPos.haxe_doc: Ensures that object has an up-to-date position transform.

calcAbsPos.haxe_doc: Internal usage Calculates the absolute object position transform. See `Object.syncPos` for a safe position sync method. This method does not ensure that object parents also have up-to-date transform nor does it clear the `Object.posChanged` flag.

emitTile.haxe_doc: Draws single Tile instance with this Object transform.

clipBounds.haxe_doc: Internal usage Clip a local bounds with our global viewport. Used during filter rendering in order to clip out areas that are off-screen and should not be rendered.

move.haxe_doc: Move the object by the specified amount along its current direction (`Object.rotation` angle).

setPosition.haxe_doc: Set the position of the object relative to its parent.

rotate.haxe_doc: Rotate the object by the given angle (in radians)

scale.haxe_doc: Scale uniformly the object by the given factor.

setScale.haxe_doc: Set the uniform scale for the object.

getChildAt.haxe_doc: Return the `n`th element among the immediate children list of this object, or `null` if there is no Object at this position.

getChildIndex.haxe_doc: Return the index of the object `o` within the immediate children list of this object, or `-1` if it is not part of the children list.

getObjectByName.haxe_doc: Search for an object recursively by name, return `null` if not found.

iterator.haxe_doc: Return an iterator over this object immediate children

contentChanged.haxe_doc: Advanced usage Called by the children of a container object if they have `parentContainer` defined in them. Primary use-case is when the child size got changed, requiring content to reevaluate positioning such as `Flow` layouts, but also can be used for other purposes.

constraintSize.haxe_doc: Advanced usage This can be called by a parent container to constraint the size of its children. Negative value mean that constraint is to be disabled. For example, `Text` constraints it's maximum width, causing word-wrap to occur within constrained area. @see `FlowProperties.constraint`

new.haxe_doc: Create a new empty object. @param parent An optional parent `h2d.Object` instance to which Object adds itself if set.

class.haxe_doc:
A base 2D class that all scene tree elements inherit from.
Serves as a virtual container that does not display anything but can contain other objects so the various transforms are inherited to its children.
Private events `Object.onAdd`, `Object.onRemove` and `Object.onHierarchyChanged` can be used to capture when Object is added/removed from the currently active scene as well as being moved withing the object tree.
Object exposes a number of properties to control position, scale and rotation of the Object relative to its parent, but they are used indirectly during rendering. Instead, they are being used to calculate the absolute matrix transform relative to the Scene. As optimization, it's not recalculated as soon as properties are modified and delayed until `Object.sync`. Absolute object position can be accessed through private variables `Object.matA`, `Object.matB`, `Object.matC`, `Object.matD`, `Object.absX` and `Object.absY`. But it should be noted that in order to ensure up-to-date values, it's advised to call `Object.syncPos` before accessing them.

color.haxe_doc: The color multiplier for the drawable. Can be used to adjust individually each of the four channels R,G,B,A (default [1,1,1,1])

smooth.haxe_doc:
By enabling smoothing, scaling the object up or down will use hardware bilinear filtering resulting in a less crisp aspect.
By default smooth is `null` in which case `Scene.defaultSmooth` value is used.

tileWrap.haxe_doc:
Enables texture uv wrap for this Drawable, causing tiles with uv exceeding the texture size to repeat instead of clamping on edges.
Note that `tileWrap` does not use the `Tile` region as a wrapping area but instead uses underlying `h3d.mat.Texture` size. This is due to implementation specifics, as it just sets the `Texture.wrap` to either `Repeat` or `Clamp`. Because of that, proper Tile tiling can be expected only when the tile covers an entire Texture area.

colorKey.haxe_doc: Setting a colorKey color value will discard all pixels that have this exact color in the tile.

colorMatrix.haxe_doc: Setting a colorMatrix will apply a color transformation. See also `adjustColor`.

colorAdd.haxe_doc: Setting colorAdd will add the amount of color of each channel R,G,B,A to the object pixels.

adjustColor.haxe_doc: Set the `Drawable.colorMatrix` value by specifying which effects to apply. Calling `adjustColor()` without arguments will reset the colorMatrix to `null`.

getDebugShaderCode.haxe_doc: Returns the built shader code, can be used for debugging shader assembly @param toHxsl Whether return an HXSL shader or the native shading language of the backend.

getShader.haxe_doc: Returns the first shader of the given shader class among the drawable shaders. @param stype The class of the shader to look up.

getShaders.haxe_doc: Returns an iterator of all drawable shaders

addShader.haxe_doc:
Add a shader to the drawable shaders.
Keep in mind, that as stated before, drawable children do not inherit Drawable properties, which includes shaders.

removeShader.haxe_doc: Remove a shader from the drawable shaders, returns true if found or false if it was not part of our shaders.

new.haxe_doc: Create a new Drawable instance with given parent. @param parent An optional parent `h2d.Object` instance to which Drawable adds itself if set.

class.haxe_doc:
A base class for all 2D objects that will draw something on the screen.
Unlike Object base class, all properties of Drawable only apply to the current object and are not inherited by its children.

tile.haxe_doc: The tile to display. See `h2d.Tile` documentation for details. If the tile is null, a pink 5x5 bitmap will be displayed instead.

width.haxe_doc:
If set, rescale the tile to match the given width, keeping the aspect ratio unless `height` is also set.
Note that both `width` and `height` are `null` by default and in order to retrieve bitmap dimensions with scaling accurately, call `getSize` method or address `tile.width/height` to get unscaled dimensions.

height.haxe_doc:
If set, rescale the tile to match the given height, keeping the aspect ratio unless `width` is also set.
Note that both `width` and `height` are `null` by default and in order to retrieve bitmap dimensions with scaling accurately, call `getSize` method or address `tile.width/height` to get unscaled dimensions.

class.haxe_doc:
Displays a single bitmap Tile on the screen.
It is a most primitive Drawable and easiest to use, but vastly inferior to others in terms of performance when used for rendering of many tiles. When dealing with many images at once, it is recommended to use batched renderers, like `h2d.SpriteBatch` or `h2d.TileGroup`.

Max.haxe_doc: The output color is the max of the source and dest colors. The blend parameters Src and Dst are ignored for this equation. `Out = MAX( Src, Dst )`

Min.haxe_doc: The output color is the min of the source and dest colors. The blend parameters Src and Dst are ignored for this equation. `Out = MAX( Src, Dst )`

enum.haxe_doc: The blending rules when rendering a Tile/Material.

x.haxe_doc: X position of the camera in world space based on anchorX.

y.haxe_doc: Y position of the camera in world space based on anchorY.

scaleX.haxe_doc: Horizontal scale factor of the camera. Scaling applied, using anchored position as pivot.

scaleY.haxe_doc: Vertical scale factor of the camera. Scaling applied, using anchored position as pivot.

rotation.haxe_doc: Rotation of the camera in radians. Camera is rotated around anchored position.

clipViewport.haxe_doc:
Enables viewport clipping. Allow to restrict rendering area of the camera to the viewport boundaries.
Does not affect the user input when Camera is set as interactive camera.

viewportX.haxe_doc: Horizontal viewport offset of the camera relative to internal scene viewport (see `h2d.Scene.scaleMode`) in scene coordinates. ( default : 0 ) Automatically scales on scene resize.

viewportY.haxe_doc: Vertical viewport offset of the camera relative to internal scene viewport (see `h2d.Scene.scaleMode`) in scene coordinates. ( default : 0 ) Automatically scales on scene resize.

viewportWidth.haxe_doc: Camera viewport width in scene coordinates. ( default : scene.width ) Automatically scales on scene resize.

viewportHeight.haxe_doc: Camera viewport height in scene coordinates. ( default: scene.height ) Automatically scales on scene resize.

anchorX.haxe_doc: Horizontal anchor position inside viewport boundaries used for positioning and resize compensation. ( default : 0 ) Value is a percentile (0..1) from left viewport edge to right viewport edge with 0.5 being center.

anchorY.haxe_doc: Vertical anchor position inside viewport boundaries used for positioning and resize compensation. ( default : 0 ) Value is a percentile (0..1) from top viewport edge to bottom viewport edge with 0.5 being center.

visible.haxe_doc:
Camera visibility.
Does not affect the user input when Camera is set as interactive camera.

follow.haxe_doc: Makes camera to follow the referenced Object position.

followRotation.haxe_doc: Enables `h2d.Object.rotation` sync between `Camera.follow` object and Camera.

remove.haxe_doc: Detaches Camera from the Scene it currently attached to.

enter.haxe_doc: Internal usage Prepares RenderContext to render the camera contents and clips viewport if necessary. Should call `Camera.exit` afterwards.

exit.haxe_doc: Internal usage Causes RenderContext to restore the state prior to camera rendering. Should be called after `Camera.enter` when rendering is finished.

sync.haxe_doc: Internal usage Synchronizes the camera transform matrix.

setScale.haxe_doc: Sets the `Camera.scaleX` and `Camera.scaleY` to given `x` and `y`.

setPosition.haxe_doc: Sets the camera position to given `x` and `y`.

move.haxe_doc: Moves the camera position by given `dx` and `dy`.

rotate.haxe_doc: Rotates the camera relative to current rotation by given `angle` in radians.

setAnchor.haxe_doc: Sets the `Camera.anchorX` and `Camera.anchorY` to given `x` and `y`.

setViewport.haxe_doc:
Sets camera viewport dimensions. If `w` or `h` arguments are 0 - scene size is used (width or height respectively).
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

setRawViewport.haxe_doc: Sets camera viewport dimensions in raw format of 0..1 percentiles.

screenXToCamera.haxe_doc:
Convert screen position into a local camera position.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

screenYToCamera.haxe_doc:
Convert screen position into a local camera position.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

cameraXToScreen.haxe_doc:
Convert local camera position to absolute screen position.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

cameraYToScreen.haxe_doc:
Convert local camera position to absolute screen position.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

sceneXToCamera.haxe_doc: Convert an absolute scene position into a local camera position. Does not represent screen position, see `Camera.screenXToCamera` to convert position with accounting of `scaleMode`.

sceneYToCamera.haxe_doc: Convert an absolute scene position into a local camera position. Does not represent screen position, see `Camera.screenYToCamera` to convert position with accounting of `scaleMode`.

cameraXToScene.haxe_doc: Convert local camera position into absolute scene position. Does not represent screen position, see `Camera.cameraXToScreen` to convert position with accounting of `scaleMode`.

cameraYToScene.haxe_doc: Convert local camera position into absolute scene position. Does not represent screen position, see `Camera.cameraYToScreen` to convert position with accounting of `scaleMode`.

eventToCamera.haxe_doc: Internal usage Convert `Event.relX` and `Event.relY` to local camera position.

screenToCamera.haxe_doc:
Convert screen position into a local camera position.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

cameraToScreen.haxe_doc:
Convert local camera position to absolute screen position.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

sceneToCamera.haxe_doc:
Convert an absolute scene position into a local camera position. Does not represent screen position, see `Camera.screenToCamera` to convert position with accounting of `scaleMode`.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

cameraToScene.haxe_doc:
Convert local camera position into absolute scene position. Does not represent screen position, see `Camera.cameraToScreen` to convert position with accounting of `scaleMode`.
Requires Camera being attached to a Scene.

class.haxe_doc:
A 2D camera representation attached to `h2d.Scene`.
Enables ability to move, scale and rotate the scene viewport.
Scene supports usage of multiple Camera instances. To configure which layers each Camera renders - `Camera.layerVisible` method should be overridden. By default, camera does not clip out the contents that are outside camera bounding box, which can be enabled through `Camera.clipViewport`.
Due to Heaps event handling structure, only one Camera instance can handle the mouse/touch input, and can be set through `h2d.Scene.interactiveCamera` variable. Note that during even handing, interactive camera does not check if the Camera itself is visible nor the layers filters as well as `clipViewport` is not applied.

buffer.haxe_doc: The primitive vertex buffer, holding its vertexes data.

indexes.haxe_doc: The primitive indexes buffer, holding its triangles indices.

refCount.haxe_doc: Current amount of references to this Primitive. Use `incref` and `decref` methods to affect this value. If it reaches 0, it will be atuomatically disposed.

triCount.haxe_doc: The number of triangles the primitive has.

vertexCount.haxe_doc: The number of vertexes the primitive has.

getCollider.haxe_doc: Return a local collider for the primitive

getBounds.haxe_doc: Return the bounds for the primitive

incref.haxe_doc: Increase reference count of the Primitive.

decref.haxe_doc: Decrease reference count of the Primitive. If recount reaches zero, Primitive is automatically disposed when last referencing mesh is removed from scene.

alloc.haxe_doc: Allocate the primitive on GPU. Used for internal usage.

selectMaterial.haxe_doc: Select the specified sub material before drawin. Used for internal usage.

render.haxe_doc: Render the primitive. Used for internal usage.

dispose.haxe_doc: Dispose the primitive, freeing the GPU memory it uses.

toString.haxe_doc: Return the primitive type.

class.haxe_doc: h3d.prim.Primitive is the base class for all 3D primitives. You can't create an instance of it and need to use one of its subclasses.

tile.haxe_doc: The Tile used as source of Texture to render.

bevel.haxe_doc:
Adds bevel cut-off at line corners.
The value is a percentile in range of 0...1, dictating at which point edges get beveled based on their angle. Value of 0 being not beveled and 1 being always beveled.

moveTo.haxe_doc: Ends the current line and starts new one at given position.

curveTo.haxe_doc: * Draws a quadratic Bezier curve using the current line style from the current drawing position to (cx, cy) and using the control point that (bx, by) specifies. * IvanK Lib port ( http://lib.ivank.net )

cubicCurveTo.haxe_doc: * Draws a cubic Bezier curve from the current drawing position to the specified anchor point. * IvanK Lib port ( http://lib.ivank.net ) * @param bx control X for start point * @param by control Y for start point * @param cx control X for end point * @param cy control Y for end point * @param dx end X * @param dy end Y * @param nsegments = 40

lineTo.haxe_doc: Draws a straight line from the current drawing position to the given position.

new.haxe_doc: Create a new Graphics instance. @param parent An optional parent `h2d.Object` instance to which Graphics adds itself if set.

class.haxe_doc:
A simple interface to draw arbitrary 2D geometry.
Usage notes: * While Graphics allows for multiple unique textures, each texture swap causes a new drawcall, and due to that it's recommended to minimize the amount of used textures per Graphics instance, ideally limiting to only one texture. * Due to how Graphics operate, removing them from the active `h2d.Scene` will cause a loss of all data.

width.haxe_doc: Width of the Interactive. Ignored if `Interactive.shape` is set.

height.haxe_doc: Height of the Interactive. Ignored if `Interactive.shape` is set.

cursor.haxe_doc: Cursor used when Interactive is under mouse cursor.

isEllipse.haxe_doc: Performs an elliptic hit-test instead of rectangular one based on `Interactive.width` and `height`. Ignored if `Interactive.shape` is set.

backgroundColor.haxe_doc: If set, Interactive will draw a `Tile` with `[width, height]` dimensions of specified color (including alpha).

enableRightButton.haxe_doc:
When enabled, interacting with secondary mouse buttons (right button/wheel) will cause `onPush`, `onClick`, `onRelease` and `onReleaseOutside` callbacks. Otherwise those callbacks will only be triggered with primary mouse button (left button).
Note that Interactive remembers only the last pressed button when pressing on it, hence pressing Interactive with the left button and then the right button would not cause `onClick` on either when releasing left button first, as pressed state is reset internally.

shape.haxe_doc: Detailed shape collider for Interactive. If set, `width` and `height` properties are ignored for collision checks.

shapeX.haxe_doc: Detailed shape X offset from Interactive.

shapeY.haxe_doc: Detailed shape Y offset from Interactive.

preventClick.haxe_doc: Reset current pressed state of the Interactive, preventing the `onClick` or `onReleaseOutside` being triggered when user releases mouse button.

focus.haxe_doc: Sets focus on this `Interactive`. If Interactive was not already focused and it receives focus - `onFocus` event is sent. Interactive won't become focused if during `onFocus` call it will set `Event.cancel` to `true`.

blur.haxe_doc: Removes focus from interactive if it's focused. If Interactive is currently focused - `onFocusLost` event will be sent. Interactive won't lose focus if during `onFocusLost` call it will set `Event.cancel` to `true`.

isOver.haxe_doc: Checks if Interactive is currently hovered by the mouse.

hasFocus.haxe_doc: Checks if Interactive is currently focused.

onOver.haxe_doc:
Sent when mouse enters Interactive hitbox area.
`Event.propagate` and `Event.cancel` are ignored during `onOver`. Propagation can be set with `onMove` event, as well as cancelling `onMove` will prevent `onOver`.

onOut.haxe_doc: Sent when mouse exits Interactive hitbox area. `Event.propagate` and `Event.cancel` are ignored during `onOut`.

onPush.haxe_doc: Sent when Interactive is pressed by the user.

onRelease.haxe_doc:
Sent when Interactive is unpressed under multiple circumstances. * Always sent if user releases mouse while it is inside Interactive hitbox area. This happens regardless if that Interactive was pressed prior or not, and due to that it's not guaranteed that `Interactive.onPush` would precede this event. `Event.kind` is set to `ERelease` during this event. * Sent before `Interactive.onReleaseOutside` if this Interactive was pressed, but released outside its hitbox area. `Event.kind` is set to `EReleaseOutside` during this event.
See `Interactive.onClick` and `Interactive.onReleaseOutside` methods for separate events that trigger only when user interacts with this particular Interactive.

onReleaseOutside.haxe_doc:
Sent when user presses the Interactive, moves the mouse outside its hitbox area and releases the mouse button.
Can be prevented to fire by calling `Interactive.preventClick` during or after `Interactive.onPush` event.
`Interactive.onRelease` is sent with `Event.kind` being `EReleaseOutside` just before this event.

onClick.haxe_doc:
Sent when the Interactive is clicked by the user.
Can be prevented to fire by calling `Interactive.preventClick` during or after `Interactive.onPush` event.
`Interactive.onRelease` is sent with `Event.kind` being `ERelease` just before this event.

onMove.haxe_doc:
Sent when user moves within the Interactive hitbox area. See `Interactive.onCheck` for event when user does not move the mouse.
Cancelling the `Event` will prevent interactive from becoming overed, causing `Interactive.onOut` if it was overed previously. Interactive would be treated as not overed as long as event is cancelled even if mouse is within the hitbox area.

onWheel.haxe_doc: Sent when user scrolls mouse wheel above the Interactive. Wheel delta can be obtained through the `Event.wheelDelta`.

onFocus.haxe_doc:
Sent when Interactive receives focus during `Interactive.focus` call.
Cancelling the `Event` will prevent the Interactive from becoming focused.

onFocusLost.haxe_doc:
Sent when Interactive lost focus either via `Interactive.blur` call or when user clicks on another Interactive/outside this Interactive hitbox area.
Cancelling the `Event` will prevent the Interactive from losing focus.

onKeyUp.haxe_doc: Sent when this Interactive is focused and user unpressed a keyboard key. Unpressed key can be accessed through `Event.keyCode`.

onKeyDown.haxe_doc: Sent when this Interactive is focused and user pressed a keyboard key. Pressed key can be accessed through `Event.keyCode`.

onCheck.haxe_doc:
Sent every frame when user hovers an Interactive but does not move the mouse. See `Interactive.onMove` for event when user moves the mouse.
Cancelling the `Event` will prevent interactive from becoming overed, causing `Interactive.onOut` if it was overed previously. Interactive would be treated as not overed as long as event is cancelled even if mouse is within the hitbox area.

onTextInput.haxe_doc: Sent when this Interactive is focused and user inputs text. Character added can be accessed through `Event.charCode`.

class.haxe_doc:
A user input handler.
Hitbox area can be a rectangle, an ellipse or an arbitrary shape (`h2d.col.Collider`).
Note that Interactive does not reports its hitbox bounds in `Object.getBounds` unless `Interactive.backgroundColor` is set, in which case `width` and `height` are reported.
By default, Interactive only reacts to primary (left) mouse button for actions, see `Interactive.enableRightButton` for details.

addChild.haxe_doc: Adds a child object `s` at the end of the layer 0. @param s An object to be added.

new.haxe_doc: Create a new Layers instance. @param parent An optional parent `h2d.Object` instance to which Layers adds itself if set.

class.haxe_doc:
A layer-based container for Objects.
Hierarchically organizes objects based on their layer. Supports per-layer Y-sorting through `Layers.ysort`.

unmask.haxe_doc: Unmasks the previously masked area from `Mask.maskWith`. @param ctx The render context to unmask.

width.haxe_doc: The width of the masked area.

height.haxe_doc: The height of the masked area.

scrollX.haxe_doc: Horizontal scroll offset of the Mask content in pixels. Can be clamped by `Mask.scrollBounds`.

scrollY.haxe_doc: Vertical scroll offset of the Mask content in pixels. Can be clamped by `Mask.scrollBounds`.

scrollBounds.haxe_doc: Optional scroll boundaries that prevent content from overscroll.

scrollTo.haxe_doc: Scroll the Mask content to the specified offset.

scrollBy.haxe_doc: Scroll the Mask content by the specified offset relative to the current scroll offset.

class.haxe_doc:
Restricts rendering area within the `[width, height]` rectangle. For more advanced masking, see `h2d.filter.AbstractMask`.
Rotation of the mask does not rotate the masked area and instead causes it to cover the bounding box of the mask.
The `Mask.maskWidth` and `Mask.unmask` can be used to mask out rendering area without direct usage of Mask instance in-between.

globalAlpha.haxe_doc: Current transparency value used for rendering objects. Automatically managed by `Object`.

buffer.haxe_doc: Temporary vertex buffer used to emit Tiles when `RenderContext.BUFFERING` is on. Otherwise it's `null`. Internal usage only.

bufPos.haxe_doc: Current temporary buffer position. Internal usage only.

scene.haxe_doc: The 2D scene attached to this RenderContext instance.

defaultSmooth.haxe_doc: Internal usage Determines texture filtering method (Linear or Nearest). Not recommended to use - assign `Scene.defaultSmooth` instead.

killAlpha.haxe_doc: When enabled, pixels with alpha value below 0.001 will be discarded.

front2back.haxe_doc: When enabled, causes `Object` to render its children in reverse order.

onBeginDraw.haxe_doc: Sent before Drawable is rendered. Drawable won't be rendered if callback returns `false`.

onEnterFilter.haxe_doc: Sent before filter begins rendering. Filter (and it's object tree) won't be rendered if callback returns `false`.

onLeaveFilter.haxe_doc: Send after filter has been rendered.

tmpBounds.haxe_doc: Internal usage Used to calculate filter rendering bounds.

hasBuffering.haxe_doc: Tells if tile buffering is enabled.

begin.haxe_doc: Internal usage Prepares RenderContext to begin rendering a new frame.

allocTarget.haxe_doc: Allocated a cached render target Texture with specified name, filter mode and current `Scene.width` and `Scene.height`. @returns Either precached Texture under same name or newly allocated one.

clear.haxe_doc: Clears current render target with specified color.

end.haxe_doc: Internal usage Performers cleanup after frame is rendered.

pushCamera.haxe_doc: Internal usage Applies Camera `cam` transform to current viewport and pushes it onto the camera stack. Should call `RenderContext.popCamera` when rendering is complete.

popCamera.haxe_doc: Internal usage Restores previous viewport state prior to camera rendering, removing it from the camera stack.

pushFilter.haxe_doc: Internal usage Prepares to render Filter and pushes provided Object onto filter stack. @returns true if filter is allowed to render, false otherwise (see `RenderContext.onEnterFilter`)

popFilter.haxe_doc: Internal usage Finalizes Filter rendering and removes top-most Object from filter stack.

pushTargets.haxe_doc: Pushes an array of render targets onto target stack.

popTarget.haxe_doc: Pops current render target from the target stack. If last texture was removed from the stack, will restore the primary render buffer as a render target.

pushRenderZone.haxe_doc:
Sets rectangular render zone area, saving previous render zone settings. To respect previous render zone area, use `RenderContext.clipRenderZone` method.
`RenderContext.popRenderZone` should be called afterwards to clear render zone stack.

clipRenderZone.haxe_doc: Pushes new render zone with respect to the old render zone settings by clipping new and old render zones, pushing the intersection area result. Used so that any call to the clipRenderZone respects the already set zone, and can't render outside of it.

drawScene.haxe_doc: Renders the assigned Scene. Same as `s2d.drawRec(s2d.renderer)`.

flush.haxe_doc: Flushes buffered tile data if one present.

beforeDraw.haxe_doc: Internal usage Should be called before performing a new draw call in order to sync shader data and other parameters.

beginDrawBatchState.haxe_doc: Prepares rendering with BatchState. Each state draw should be preceded with `swapTexture` call.

swapTexture.haxe_doc: Swap current active texture and prepares for next drawcall.

beginDrawObject.haxe_doc: Prepares rendering of the Drawable object with specified texture. @returns true if rendering is prepared, false otherwise (see `RenderContext.onBeginDraw`)

beginDrawBatch.haxe_doc: Begins buffered Tile render of the Drawable object. @returns true if rendering is prepared, false otherwise (see `RenderContext.onBeginDraw`)

new.haxe_doc: Create a new RenderContext and attach it to specified Scene. @param scene The scene which RenderContext will render.

class.haxe_doc:
A 2D scene renderer.
Passed during `Object.sync` and `Object.drawRec` and can be accessed directly via `Scene.renderer`.

Left.haxe_doc: Anchor Scene viewport horizontally to the left side of the window. When passed to `verticalAlign` it will be treated as Center.

Right.haxe_doc: Anchor Scene viewport horizontally to the right side of the window. When passed to `verticalAlign` it will be treated as Center.

Center.haxe_doc: Anchor to the center of the window.

Top.haxe_doc: Anchor Scene viewport vertically to the top of the window. When passed to `horizontalAlign` it will be treated as Center.

Bottom.haxe_doc: Anchor Scene viewport vertically to the bottom of the window. When passed to `horizontalAlign` it will be treated as Center.

enum.haxe_doc: Viewport alignment when scaling mode supports it. See `ScaleMode`.

Resize.haxe_doc: Matches scene size to window size. `width` and `height` of Scene will match window size. Default scaling mode.

Zoom.haxe_doc:
Upscales/downscales the Scene internal viewport according to `level` and matches Scene size to `ceil(window size / level)`.
With `800x600` window, `Zoom(2)` will result in the `400x300` Scene size upscaled to fill the entire window.

enum.haxe_doc:
Scaling mode of the 2D Scene.
Set via `Scene.scaleMode`.
See ScaleMode2D sample for usage showcase.

width.haxe_doc: The current width (in pixels) of the scene. Can change if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes.

height.haxe_doc: The current height (in pixels) of the scene. Can change if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes.

viewportA.haxe_doc: Viewport horizontal scale transform value. Converts from scene space to screen space of [0, 2] range.

viewportD.haxe_doc: Viewport vertical scale transform value. Converts from scene space to screen space of [0, 2] range.

viewportX.haxe_doc: Horizontal viewport offset relative to top-left corner of the window. Can change if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes. Offset is in screen-space coordinates: [-1, 1] where 0 is center of the window.

viewportY.haxe_doc: Vertical viewport offset relative to top-left corner of the window. Can change if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes. Offset is in screen-space coordinates: [-1, 1] where 0 is center of the window.

offsetX.haxe_doc: Horizontal viewport offset relative to top-left corner of the window in pixels. Assigned if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes.

offsetY.haxe_doc: Vertical viewport offset relative to top-left corner of the window in pixels. Assigned if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes.

viewportScaleX.haxe_doc:
Horizontal scale of a scene when rendering to the screen.
Can change if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes.

viewportScaleY.haxe_doc:
Vertical scale of a scene when rendering to the screen.
Can change if the screen gets resized or `scaleMode` changes.

mouseX.haxe_doc: The current mouse X coordinates (in pixels) relative to the current `Scene.interactiveCamera`.

mouseY.haxe_doc: The current mouse Y coordinates (in pixels) relative to the current `Scene.interactiveCamera`.

zoom.haxe_doc: The zoom factor of the scene, allows to set a fixed x2, x4 etc. zoom for pixel art When setting a zoom > 0, the scene resize will be automatically managed.

scaleMode.haxe_doc:
Scene scaling mode.
Important thing to keep in mind - Scene does not clip rendering to it's scaled size and graphics can render outside of it. However `RenderContext.drawTile` (and consecutively `Object.emitTile`) does check for those bounds and will clip out tiles that are outside of the scene bounds.

cameras.haxe_doc:
List of all cameras attached to the Scene. Should contain at least one camera to render (created by default).
Override `h2d.Camera.layerVisible` method to filter out specific layers from camera rendering.
To add or remove cameras use `Scene.addCamera` and `Scene.removeCamera` methods.

camera.haxe_doc: Alias to the first camera in the camera list: `cameras[0]`

interactiveCamera.haxe_doc:
Camera instance that handles the scene events.
Due to Heaps structure, only one Camera can work with the Interactives. Contrary to rendering, event handling does not check if layer is visible for the camera or not.
Should never be null. When set, if Camera does not belong to the Scene, it will be added with `Scene.addCamera`. Would cause an exception when trying to remove current interactive camera from the list.

defaultSmooth.haxe_doc: Controls the default value for `h2d.Drawable.smooth`. Default: `false`

renderer.haxe_doc: The current Scene renderer. Can be customized.

"zoom is deprecated, use scaleMode = Zoom(v) instead"

removeCamera.haxe_doc: Removes the Camera from the Scene camera list. Attempting to remove current `Scene.interactiveCamera` would cause an exception.

setFixedSize.haxe_doc: Set the fixed size for the scene, will prevent automatic scene resizing when screen size changes.

checkResize.haxe_doc: Recalculates the scene viewport parameters based on `scaleMode`.

removeEventListener.haxe_doc: Remove a previously added event listener, returns false it was not part of the event listeners.

dispose.haxe_doc:
Dispose the scene and all its children, freeing used GPU memory.
If Scene was allocated, causes `Object.onRemove` on all Scene objects.

setElapsedTime.haxe_doc: Internal usage Before `Scene.render` or `Scene.sync` are called, allows to set how much time has elapsed (in seconds) since the last frame in order to update scene animations. This is managed automatically by hxd.App.

syncOnly.haxe_doc: Synchronize the scene without rendering, updating all objects and animations by the given amount of time, in seconds.

render.haxe_doc: Internal usage Render the scene on the screen.

iy.haxe_doc: An integer vertical position of the Tile on the Texture. Alias to `Math.floor(tile.y)`.

switchTexture.haxe_doc:
Changes this Tile underlying texture to one used in the specified Tile.
If Tile was scaled, new uv will cover new width and height instead of the original unscaled one.
@param t The Tile used as a source of the Texture instance.
It's possible to switch texture by referring the Texture instance directly, by using access hacks: ```haxe @:privateAccess tile.setTexture(myTextureInstance); ```

center.haxe_doc:
Returns a new Tile with shifting origin point (`dx` and `dy`) to the tile center.
To modify this Tile origin point, use `Tile.setCenterRatio`.

setCenterRatio.haxe_doc: Sets `dx` / `dy` as origin point dictated by `px` / `py` with a default being center.

flipX.haxe_doc: Flips the Tile horizontally. Note that `dx` is flipped as well.

flipY.haxe_doc: Flips the Tile vertically. Note that `dy` is flipped as well.

setPosition.haxe_doc: Set the Tile position in the texture to the specified coordinate.

setSize.haxe_doc: Set the Tile size in the texture to the specified dimensions.

scaleToSize.haxe_doc:
Rescales the Tile to be of the set width and height, but without affecting the uv coordinates.
Using this method allows to upscale/downscale Tiles, but creates a mismatch between the tile uv and width/height values. Due to that, using any methods that modify the uv value will cause the new uv to treat scaled width and height as true dimensions and can lead to unexpected results if not accounted for.

scrollDiscrete.haxe_doc: Scrolls the texture position by specified amount.

dispose.haxe_doc: Disposes of the Tile and its underlying Texture. Note that if Texture is used by other Tile instances, it will cause them to point at a disposed texture and can lead to errors.

clone.haxe_doc: Create a copy of this Tile instance.

class.haxe_doc:
A core 2D rendering component representing a region of an underlying `h3d.mat.Texture`.
Tiles cannot be created directly, and instances are created with the following methods: * Via the Resource Management system: `hxd.res.Image.toTile`. * From pre-existing Texture: `Tile.fromTexture`. * From pre-existing `BitmapData` or `Pixels`: `Tile.fromBitmap` and `Tile.fromPixels` (as well as `Tile.autoCut`). * From solid color: `Tile.fromColor`. * From previously existing Tile instance via various methods, such as `Tile.sub`.

autoBounds.haxe_doc: When enabled, rendering bounds of the filter will be expanded by `Filter.boundsExtend` in all directions. Otherwise filter should provide custom bounds through `Filter.getBounds` call. Default : true.

boundsExtend.haxe_doc: Rendering texture boundaries extent. Increases the rendering area by twice the `Filter.boundsExtend` value. Automatically applied to object bounds when `autoBounds = true` or `Filter.getBounds` is not overridden. Does not affect boundaries when `autoBounds = true` and `boundsExtend` is less than 0.

enable.haxe_doc: When filter is disabled, attached object will render as usual.

getBounds.haxe_doc: Method should populate `bounds` with rendering boundaries of the Filter for Object `s`. Initial `bounds` contents are undefined and it's recommended to either clear them or call `s.getBounds(s, bounds)`. Only used when `Filter.autoBounds` is `false`. By default uses given Object bounds and extends them with `Filter.boundsExtend`. Compared to `autoBounds = true`, negative `boundsExtend` is still applied, causing rendering area to shrink.

draw.haxe_doc: Renders the filter onto Texture in `input` Tile.

class.haxe_doc:
The base filter class, you can extend it in order to define your own filters, although ShaderFilter will be the most straightforward way to define simple custom filter.
Keep in mind that filters use internal Object resolution to render its content, hence scaling of the filtered object would not increase the rendering resolution. For example, 20x20px `Bitmap` with `scale = 2` will render onto 20x20 filter texture if filter is attached to it directly, but if filter is attached to the parent of that bitmap, filter will render 40x40 texture. Another thing to be aware of, is that `Scene.scaleMode` does not affect filter resolution either, and upscaling contents with `scaleMode` would not upscale the resolution of filtered content.
Filters limit their render area dictated by bound object boundaries, `Filter.autoBounds` and `Filter.boundsExtend` variables and `Filter.getBounds` method. See their respective docs for details.
For optimization purposes, rendering boundaries are clipped by scene viewport and nothing will be rendered offscreen.

For instance a 4:3 screen will have a lower horizontal FOV than a 16:9 one, however the vertical FOV remains constant. Use setFovX to initialize fovY based on an horizontal FOV and an initial screen ratio.

unproject.haxe_doc: Transforms a 2D screen position into the 3D one according to the current camera. The screenX and screenY values must be in the [-1,1] range. The camZ value represents the normalized z in the frustum in the [0,1] range. [unproject] can be used to get the ray from the camera position to a given screen position by using two different camZ values. For instance the 3D ray between unproject(0,0,0) and unproject(0,0,1) is the center axis of the 3D frustum.

save.haxe_doc: Save the discarded list, allow to perfom some filters, then call "load" to restore passes

load.haxe_doc: load state that was save() before

clear.haxe_doc: Put all passes into discarded list

filter.haxe_doc: Filter current passes, add results to discarded list

getFiltered.haxe_doc: Iterate on all discarded elements, if any

begin.haxe_doc: Call begin() before starting to add vertexes/indexes to the primitive. The count value is the number of vertexes you will add, it will automatically flush() if it doesn't fit into the current buffer.

addPoint.haxe_doc: This is similar to addVertexValue for X Y and Z, but will also update the bounds if you wish to have them calculated.

flush.haxe_doc: Flush the current buffer. It is required to call begin() after a flush()

m.e: { stride : -1, scale : 1., rotation : 0., dz : 0., dy : 0., dx : 0. }

add.haxe_doc: Adds a complete object to the primitive, with custom position,scale,rotation. See addSub for complete documentation.

m.e: { mat : null, color : 1., deltaV : 0., deltaU : 0., stride : -1, scale : 1., rotation : 0., dz : 0., dy : 0., dx : 0. }

addSub.haxe_doc: Adds a buffer to the primitive, with custom position,scale,rotation. The buffer can have more stride than the BigPrimitive, but not less. It is assumed that the buffer contains [X,Y,Z,NX,NY,NZ,U,V,R,G,B] (depending on his stride) so the different offsets are applied to the corresponding components. If hasTangent=true, we have [TX,TY,TZ] just after normal. However if the stride is 5, we assume [X,Y,Z,U,V] If mat is not null, it overrides dx, dy, dz, rotation, scale

class.haxe_doc: Vertex buffers are limited to 65K vertexes because of the 16-bits limitation of the index buffers. BigPrimitive allows you to easily create large buffers by spliting the buffers.

tmpMat.haxe_doc: Set the position, scale and rotation of the object relative to its parent based on the specified transform matrix.

parent.haxe_doc: The parent object in the scene tree.

numChildren.haxe_doc: How many immediate children this object has.

name.haxe_doc: The name of the object, can be used to retrieve an object within a tree by using `getObjectByName` (default null)

x.haxe_doc: The x position of the object relative to its parent.

y.haxe_doc: The y position of the object relative to its parent.

z.haxe_doc: The z position of the object relative to its parent.

scaleX.haxe_doc: The amount of scaling along the X axis of this object (default 1.0)

scaleY.haxe_doc: The amount of scaling along the Y axis of this object (default 1.0)

scaleZ.haxe_doc: The amount of scaling along the Z axis of this object (default 1.0)

visible.haxe_doc: Is the object and its children are displayed on screen (default true).

follow.haxe_doc: Follow a given object or joint as if it was our parent. Ignore defaultTransform when set.

followPositionOnly.haxe_doc: When follow is set, only follow the position and ignore both scale and rotation.

defaultTransform.haxe_doc: This is an additional optional transformation that is performed before other local transformations. It is used by the animation system.

culled.haxe_doc: Inform that the object is not to be displayed and his animation doesn't have to be sync. Unlike visible, this doesn't apply to children unless inheritCulled is set to true.

alwaysSync.haxe_doc: When an object is not visible or culled, its animation does not get synchronized unless you set alwaysSync=true

inheritCulled.haxe_doc: When enabled, the culled flag and culling collider is inherited by children objects.

ignoreBounds.haxe_doc: When enabled, the object bounds are ignored when using getBounds()

ignoreCollide.haxe_doc: When enabled, the object is ignored when using getCollider()

allowSerialize.haxe_doc: When enabled, the object can be serialized (default : true)

ignoreParentTransform.haxe_doc: When enabled, the object will not follow its parent transform

lightCameraCenter.haxe_doc: When selecting the lights to apply to this object, we will use the camera target as reference instead of the object absolute position. This is useful for very large objects so they can get good lighting.

cullingCollider.haxe_doc: When set, collider shape will be used for automatic frustum culling. If `inheritCulled` is true, collider will be inherited to children unless they have their own collider set.

cullingColliderInherited.haxe_doc: Indicates that current cullingCollider is currently inherited from a parent object

playAnimation.haxe_doc: Create an animation instance bound to the object, set it as currentAnimation and play it.

switchToAnimation.haxe_doc: Change the current animation. This animation should be an instance that was previously created by playAnimation.

stopAnimation.haxe_doc: Stop the current animation. If recursive is set to true, all children will also stop their animation

applyAnimationTransform.haxe_doc: When an object is loaded, its position scale and rotation will always be set to the default values (0 for position/rotation and 1 for scale). If it's part of a group/scene or if it's animated, then its position/rotation/scale will be stored into the defaultTransform matrix. Calling this function will reset the defaultTransform to null and instead initialize x/y/z/rotation/scale properties. This will not change the actual position of the object but allows you to move the object more freely on your own. Do not use on an object that is currently being animated, since it will set again defaultTransform and apply twice the transformation.

getObjectsCount.haxe_doc: Return the total number of children, recursively.

getMaterialByName.haxe_doc: Search for a material recursively by name, return it or null if not found.

contains.haxe_doc: Tells if the object is contained into this object children, recursively.

find.haxe_doc: Find a single object in the tree by calling `f` on each and returning the first not-null value returned, or null if not found.

findAll.haxe_doc: Find several objects in the tree by calling `f` on each and returning all the not-null values returned.

getMaterials.haxe_doc: Return all materials in the tree.

localToGlobal.haxe_doc: Convert a local position (or [0,0] if pt is null) relative to the object origin into an absolute global position, applying all the inherited transforms.

globalToLocal.haxe_doc: Convert an absolute global position into a local position relative to the object origin, applying all the inherited transforms.

getInvPos.haxe_doc: Returns the updated inverse position matrix. Please note that this is not a copy and should not be modified.

getBounds.haxe_doc: Return the bounds of this object and all its children, in absolute global coordinates.

getMeshes.haxe_doc: Return all meshes part of this tree

getMeshByName.haxe_doc: Search for an mesh recursively by name, return null if not found.

getObjectByName.haxe_doc: Search for an object recursively by name, return null if not found.

clone.haxe_doc: Make a copy of the object and all its children.

addChild.haxe_doc: Add a child object at the end of the children list.

addChildAt.haxe_doc: Insert a child object at the specified position of the children list.

iterVisibleMeshes.haxe_doc: Iterate on all mesh that are currently visible and not culled in the tree. Call `callb` for each mesh found.

removeChild.haxe_doc: Remove the given object from our immediate children list if it's part of it.

removeChildren.haxe_doc: Remove all children from our immediate children list

remove.haxe_doc: Same as parent.removeChild(this), but does nothing if parent is null. In order to capture add/removal from scene, you can override onAdd/onRemove/onParentChanged

getScene.haxe_doc: Return the Scene this object is part of, or null if not added to a Scene.

getAbsPos.haxe_doc: Returns the updated absolute position matrix. Please note that this is not a copy so it should not be modified.

getRelPos.haxe_doc: Returns the position matrix relative to another scene object

isMesh.haxe_doc: Tell if the object is a Mesh.

toMesh.haxe_doc: If the object is a Mesh, return the corresponding Mesh. If not, throw an exception.

getCollider.haxe_doc: Build and return the global absolute recursive collider for the object. Returns null if no collider was found or if ignoreCollide was set to true.

getGlobalCollider.haxe_doc: Same as getLocalCollider, but returns an absolute collider instead of a local one.

getLocalCollider.haxe_doc: Build and returns the local relative not-recursive collider for the object, or null if this object does not have a collider. Does not check for ignoreCollide.

setPosition.haxe_doc: Set the position of the object relative to its parent.

getTransform.haxe_doc: Returns the local position, scale and rotation of the object relative to its parent.

rotate.haxe_doc: Rotate around the current rotation axis by the specified angles (in radian).

setRotation.haxe_doc: Set the rotation using the specified angles (in radian).

setRotationAxis.haxe_doc: Set the rotation using the specified axis and angle of rotation around it (in radian).

setDirection.haxe_doc: Set the rotation using the specified look at direction

getLocalDirection.haxe_doc: Return the direction in which the object rotation is currently oriented to

getRotationQuat.haxe_doc: Return the quaternion representing the current object rotation. Dot not modify as it's not a copy.

setRotationQuat.haxe_doc: Set the quaternion representing the current object rotation. Dot not modify the value afterwards as no copy is made.

scale.haxe_doc: Scale uniformly the object by the given factor.

setScale.haxe_doc: Set the uniform scale for the object.

toString.haxe_doc: Return both class name and object name if any.

getChildAt.haxe_doc: Return the `n`th element among our immediate children list, or null if there is no.

getChildIndex.haxe_doc: Return the index of the object `o` within our immediate children list, or `-1` if it is not part of our children list.

iterator.haxe_doc: Return an iterator over this object immediate children

new.haxe_doc: Create a new empty object, and adds it to the parent object if not null.

class.haxe_doc: h3d.scene.Object is the base 3D class that all scene tree elements inherit from. It can be used to create a virtual container that does not display anything but can contain other objects so the various transforms are inherited to its children.

primitive.haxe_doc: The primitive of the mesh: the list of vertexes and indices necessary to display the mesh.

material.haxe_doc: The material of the mesh: the properties used to display it (texture, color, shaders, etc.)

getMeshMaterials.haxe_doc: Return all materials for the current object.

new.haxe_doc: Creates a new mesh with given primitive, material and parent object. If material is not specified, a new default material is created for the current renderer.

class.haxe_doc: h3d.scene.Mesh is the base class for all 3D objects displayed on screen. Unlike Object base class, all properties of Mesh only apply to the current object and are not inherited by its children.

is3D.haxe_doc: Setting is3D to true will switch from a screen space line (constant size whatever the distance) to a world space line

preciseShape.haxe_doc: If several interactive conflicts, the preciseShape (if defined) can be used to distinguish between the two.

priority.haxe_doc: In case of conflicting shapes, usually the one in front of the camera is prioritized, unless you set an higher priority.

cancelEvents.haxe_doc: Set the default `cancel` mode (see `hxd.Event`), default to false.

propagateEvents.haxe_doc: Set the default `propagate` mode (see `hxd.Event`), default to false.

bestMatch.haxe_doc: Is it required to find the best hit point in a complex mesh or any hit possible point will be enough (default = false, faster).

preventClick.haxe_doc: This can be called during or after a push event in order to prevent the release from triggering a click.

onOver.haxe_doc: Sent when mouse enters Interactive hitbox area. `event.propagate` and `event.cancel` are ignored during `onOver`. Propagation can be set with `onMove` event, as well as cancelling `onMove` will prevent `onOver`.

onOut.haxe_doc: Sent when mouse exits Interactive hitbox area. `event.propagate` and `event.cancel` are ignored during `onOut`.

onPush.haxe_doc: Sent when Interactive is pressed by user.

onRelease.haxe_doc: Sent on multiple conditions. A. Always sent if user releases mouse while it is inside Interactive hitbox area. This happends regardless if that Interactive was pressed prior or not. B. Sent before `onReleaseOutside` if this Interactive was pressed, but released outside it's bounds. For first case `event.kind` will be `ERelease`, for second case - `EReleaseOutside`. See `onClick` and `onReleaseOutside` functions for separate events that trigger only when user interacts with this particular Interactive.

onReleaseOutside.haxe_doc: Sent when user presses Interactive, moves mouse outside and releases it. This event fired only on Interactive that user pressed, but released mouse after moving it outside of Interactive hitbox area.

onClick.haxe_doc: Sent when Interactive is clicked by user. This event fired only on Interactive that user pressed and released when mouse is inside Interactive hitbox area.

addShader.haxe_doc: Inject a post process shader for the current frame. Shaders are reset after each render.

lightSystem.haxe_doc: The scene light system. Can be customized.

renderer.haxe_doc: The scene renderer. Can be customized.

addEventListener.haxe_doc: Add an event listener that will capture all events not caught by an h2d.Interactive

removeEventListener.haxe_doc: Remove a previously added event listener, return false it was not part of our event listeners.

dispose.haxe_doc: Free the GPU memory for this Scene and its children

setElapsedTime.haxe_doc: Before render() or sync() are called, allow to set how much time has elapsed (in seconds) since the last frame in order to update scene animations. This is managed automatically by hxd.App

hardwarePick.haxe_doc: Use GPU rendering to pick a model at the given pixel position. hardwarePick() will check all scene visible meshes bounds against a ray cast with current camera, then draw them into a 1x1 pixel texture with a specific shader. The texture will then be read and the color will identify the object that was rendered at this pixel. This is a very precise way of doing scene picking since it performs exactly the same transformations (skinning, custom shaders, etc.) but might be more costly than using CPU colliders. Please note that when done during/after rendering, this might clear the screen on some platforms so it should always be done before rendering.

syncOnly.haxe_doc: Synchronize the scene without rendering, updating all objects and animations by the given amount of time, in seconds.

computeStatic.haxe_doc: Perform a rendering with `RendererContext.computingStatic=true`, allowing the computation of static shadow maps, etc.

render.haxe_doc: Render the scene on screen. Internal usage only.

serializeScene.haxe_doc: Serialize the scene content as HSD bytes (see hxd.fmt.hsd package). Requires -lib hxbit

new.haxe_doc: Create a new scene. A default 3D scene is already available in `hxd.App.s3d`

class.haxe_doc: h3d.scene.Scene is the root class for a 3D scene. All root objects are added to it before being drawn on screen.

additiveLighting.haxe_doc: In the additive lighting model (by default), the lights are added after the ambient. In the new non additive ligthning model, the lights will be modulated against the ambient, so an ambient of 1 will reduce lights intensities to 0.

abstract.haxe_doc: Get information about the call stack.

This type unifies with any function type.
It is intended to be used as a type parameter constraint. If used as a real type, the underlying type will be `Dynamic`.

This type unifies with an enum instance if all constructors of the enum require no arguments.
It is intended to be used as a type parameter constraint. If used as a real type, the underlying type will be `Dynamic`.

This type unifies with anything but `Void`.
It is intended to be used as a type parameter constraint. If used as a real type, the underlying type will be `Dynamic`.

This type unifies with any instance of classes that have a constructor which
* is `public` and * unifies with the type used for type parameter `T`.
If a type parameter `A` is assigned to a type parameter `B` which is constrained to `Constructible<T>`, A must be explicitly constrained to `Constructible<T>` as well.
It is intended to be used as a type parameter constraint. If used as a real type, the underlying type will be `Dynamic`.

DynamicAccess is an abstract type for working with anonymous structures that are intended to hold collections of objects by the string key.
For example, these types of structures are often created from JSON.
Basically, it wraps `Reflect` calls in a `Map`-like interface.

run.haxe_doc: Start the main loop. Depending on the platform, this can return immediately or will only return when the application exits.

class.haxe_doc: If `haxe.MainLoop` is kept from DCE, then we will insert an `haxe.EntryPoint.run()` call just at then end of `main()`. This class can be redefined by custom frameworks so they can handle their own main loop logic.

abstract.haxe_doc:
A typed interface for bit flags. This is not a real object, only a typed interface for an actual Int. Each flag can be tested/set with the corresponding enum instance. Up to 32 flags can be stored that way.
Enum constructor indices are preserved from Haxe syntax, so the first declared is index 0, the next index 1 etc. The methods are optimized if the enum instance is passed directly, e.g. as `has(EnumCtor)`. Otherwise `Type.enumIndex()` reflection is used.

getName.haxe_doc:
Returns the name of enum `e`, including its path.
If `e` is inside a package, the package structure is returned dot- separated, with another dot separating the enum name:
pack1.pack2.(...).packN.EnumName
If `e` is a sub-type of a Haxe module, that module is not part of the package structure.
If `e` has no package, the enum name is returned.
If `e` is `null`, the result is unspecified.
The enum name does not include any type parameters.

createByName.haxe_doc:
Creates an instance of enum `e` by calling its constructor `constr` with arguments `params`.
If `e` or `constr` is `null`, or if enum `e` has no constructor named `constr`, or if the number of elements in `params` does not match the expected number of constructor arguments, or if any argument has an invalid type, the result is unspecified.

createByIndex.haxe_doc:
Creates an instance of enum `e` by calling its constructor number `index` with arguments `params`.
The constructor indices are preserved from Haxe syntax, so the first declared is index 0, the next index 1 etc.
If `e` or `index` is `null`, or if enum `e` has no constructor corresponding to index `index`, or if the number of elements in `params` does not match the expected number of constructor arguments, or if any argument has an invalid type, the result is unspecified.

createAll.haxe_doc:
Returns a list of all constructors of enum `e` that require no arguments.
This may return the empty Array `[]` if all constructors of `e` require arguments.
Otherwise an instance of `e` constructed through each of its non- argument constructors is returned, in the order of the constructor declaration.
If `e` is `null`, the result is unspecified.

getConstructors.haxe_doc:
Returns a list of the names of all constructors of enum `e`.
The order of the constructor names in the returned Array is preserved from the original syntax.
If `c` is `null`, the result is unspecified.

class.haxe_doc:
This class provides advanced methods on enums. It is ideally used with `using EnumTools` and then acts as an [extension](https://haxe.org/manual/lf-static-extension.html) to the `enum` types.
If the first argument to any of the methods is `null`, the result is unspecified.

equals.haxe_doc:
Recursively compares two enum instances `a` and `b` by value.
Unlike `a == b`, this function performs a deep equality check on the arguments of the constructors (if there are any).
If `a` or `b` are `null`, the result is unspecified.

getName.haxe_doc:
Returns the constructor name of enum instance `e`.
The result String does not contain any constructor arguments.
If `e` is `null`, the result is unspecified.

getParameters.haxe_doc:
Returns a list of the constructor arguments of enum instance `e`.
If `e` has no arguments, the result is `[]`.
Otherwise the result are the values that were used as arguments to `e`, in the order of their declaration.
If `e` is `null`, the result is unspecified.

getIndex.haxe_doc:
Returns the index of enum instance `e`.
This corresponds to the original syntactic position of `e`. The index of the first declared constructor is 0, the next one is 1 etc.
If `e` is `null`, the result is unspecified.

class.haxe_doc:
This class provides advanced methods on enum values. It is ideally used with `using EnumValueTools` and then acts as an [extension](https://haxe.org/manual/lf-static-extension.html) to the `EnumValue` types.
If the first argument to any of the methods is `null`, the result is unspecified.

native.haxe_doc: Native exception, which caused this exception.

toString.haxe_doc: Returns exception message.

new.haxe_doc:
Create a new Exception instance.
The `previous` argument could be used for exception chaining.
The `native` argument is for internal usage only. There is no need to provide `native` argument manually and no need to keep it upon extending `haxe.Exception` unless you know what you're doing.

abstract.haxe_doc: Int32 provides a 32-bit integer with consistent overflow behavior across all platforms.
A cross-platform signed 64-bit integer. Int64 instances can be created from two 32-bit words using `Int64.make()`.

typedef.haxe_doc: This typedef will fool `@:coreApi` into thinking that we are using the same underlying type, even though it might be different on specific platforms.

parse.haxe_doc:
Parses given JSON-encoded `text` and returns the resulting object.
JSON objects are parsed into anonymous structures and JSON arrays are parsed into `Array<Dynamic>`.
If given `text` is not valid JSON, an exception will be thrown.
@see https://haxe.org/manual/std-Json-parsing.html

stringify.haxe_doc:
Encodes the given `value` and returns the resulting JSON string.
If `replacer` is given and is not null, it is used to retrieve the actual object to be encoded. The `replacer` function takes two parameters, the key and the value being encoded. Initial key value is an empty string.
If `space` is given and is not null, the result will be pretty-printed. Successive levels will be indented by this string.
@see https://haxe.org/manual/std-Json-encoding.html

class.haxe_doc:
Cross-platform JSON API: it will automatically use the optimized native API if available. Use `-D haxeJSON` to force usage of the Haxe implementation even if a native API is found: This will provide extra encoding features such as enums (replaced by their index) and StringMaps.
@see https://haxe.org/manual/std-Json.html

formatOutput.haxe_doc: Format the output of `trace` before printing it.

class.haxe_doc: Log primarily provides the `trace()` method, which is invoked upon a call to `trace()` in Haxe code.

isBlocking.haxe_doc: Tells if the event can lock the process from exiting (default:true)

stop.haxe_doc: Stop the event from firing anymore.

add.haxe_doc: Add a pending event to be run into the main loop.

tick.haxe_doc: Run the pending events. Return the time for next event.

typedef.haxe_doc:
`PosInfos` is a magic type which can be used to generate position information into the output for debugging use.
If a function has a final optional argument of this type, i.e. `(..., ?pos:haxe.PosInfos)`, each call to that function which does not assign a value to that argument has its position added as call argument.
This can be used to track positions of calls in e.g. a unit testing framework.

delay.haxe_doc:
Invokes `f` after `time_ms` milliseconds.
This is a convenience function for creating a new Timer instance with `time_ms` as argument, binding its `run()` method to `f` and then stopping `this` Timer upon the first invocation.
If `f` is `null`, the result is unspecified.

stop.haxe_doc:
Stops `this` Timer.
After calling this method, no additional invocations of `this.run` will occur.
It is not possible to restart `this` Timer once stopped.

run.haxe_doc:
This method is invoked repeatedly on `this` Timer.
It can be overridden in a subclass, or rebound directly to a custom function:
```haxe var timer = new haxe.Timer(1000); // 1000ms delay timer.run = function() { ... } ```
Once bound, it can still be rebound to different functions until `this` Timer is stopped through a call to `this.stop`.

new.haxe_doc:
Creates a new timer that will run every `time_ms` milliseconds.
After creating the Timer instance, it calls `this.run` repeatedly, with delays of `time_ms` milliseconds, until `this.stop` is called.
The first invocation occurs after `time_ms` milliseconds, not immediately.
The accuracy of this may be platform-dependent.

class.haxe_doc:
The `Timer` class allows you to create asynchronous timers on platforms that support events.
The intended usage is to create an instance of the `Timer` class with a given interval, set its `run()` method to a custom function to be invoked and eventually call `stop()` to stop the `Timer`.
Note that a running `Timer` may or may not prevent the program to exit automatically when `main()` returns.
It is also possible to extend this class and override its `run()` method in the child class.

unwrap.haxe_doc:
Extract an originally thrown value.
This method must return the same value on subsequent calls. Used internally for catching non-native exceptions. Do _not_ override unless you know what you are doing.

class.haxe_doc:
An exception containing arbitrary value.
This class is automatically used for throwing values, which don't extend `haxe.Exception` or native exception type. For example: ```haxe throw "Terrible error"; ``` will be compiled to ```haxe throw new ValueException("Terrible error"); ```
Calculates the Adler32 of the given Bytes.

ofString.haxe_doc: Returns the `Bytes` representation of the given `String`, using the specified encoding (UTF-8 by default).

ofData.haxe_doc: Returns the `Bytes` representation of the given `BytesData`.

fill.haxe_doc: Sets `len` consecutive bytes starting from index `pos` of `this` instance to `value`.

getFloat.haxe_doc: Returns the IEEE single-precision value at the given position `pos` (in little-endian encoding). Result is unspecified if `pos` is outside the bounds.

setFloat.haxe_doc: Stores the given IEEE single-precision value `v` at the given position `pos` in little-endian encoding. Result is unspecified if writing outside of bounds.

getUInt16.haxe_doc: Returns the 16-bit unsigned integer at the given position `pos` (in little-endian encoding).

setUInt16.haxe_doc: Stores the given 16-bit unsigned integer `v` at the given position `pos` (in little-endian encoding).

getInt32.haxe_doc: Returns the 32-bit integer at the given position `pos` (in little-endian encoding).

setInt32.haxe_doc: Stores the given 32-bit integer `v` at the given position `pos` (in little-endian encoding).

getString.haxe_doc: Returns the `len`-bytes long string stored at the given position `pos`, interpreted with the given `encoding` (UTF-8 by default).

toString.haxe_doc: Returns a `String` representation of the bytes interpreted as UTF-8.

RawNative.haxe_doc: Output the string the way the platform represent it in memory. This is the most efficient but is platform-specific

enum.haxe_doc: String binary encoding supported by Haxe I/O

BYTES_PER_ELEMENT.haxe_doc: Returns a number value of the element size. 1 in the case of an `Uint8Array`.

from.haxe_doc: Creates a new `Uint8Array` from an array-like or iterable object. See also [Array.from()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/from).
Creates a new `Uint8Array` from an array-like or iterable object. See also [Array.from()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/from).

of.haxe_doc: Creates a new `Uint8Array` with a variable number of arguments. See also [Array.of()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/of).

BYTES_PER_ELEMENT_.haxe_doc: Returns a number value of the element size.

buffer.haxe_doc: Returns the `ArrayBuffer` referenced by the `Uint8Array` Fixed at construction time and thus read only.

byteLength.haxe_doc: Returns the length (in bytes) of the `Uint8Array` from the start of its `ArrayBuffer`. Fixed at construction time and thus read only.

byteOffset.haxe_doc: Returns the offset (in bytes) of the `Uint8Array` from the start of its `ArrayBuffer`. Fixed at construction time and thus read only.

length.haxe_doc: Returns the number of elements hold in the `Uint8Array`. Fixed at construction time and thus read only.

copyWithin.haxe_doc: Copies a sequence of array elements within the array. See also [Array.prototype.copyWithin()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/copyWithin).

entries.haxe_doc: Returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the key/value pairs for each index in the array. See also [Array.prototype.entries()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/entries).

every.haxe_doc: Tests whether all elements in the array pass the test provided by a function. See also [Array.prototype.every()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/every).

Documentation [Uint8Array](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Uint8Array) by [Mozilla Contributors](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Uint8Array$history), licensed under [CC-BY-SA 2.5](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5/).

sort.haxe_doc:
Sorts Array `a` according to the comparison function `cmp`, where `cmp(x,y)` returns 0 if `x == y`, a positive Int if `x > y` and a negative Int if `x < y`.
This operation modifies Array `a` in place.
This operation is stable: The order of equal elements is preserved.
If `a` or `cmp` are null, the result is unspecified.

class.haxe_doc: ArraySort provides a stable implementation of merge sort through its `sort` method. It should be used instead of `Array.sort` in cases where the order of equal elements has to be retained on all targets.
